Summary: Explains the use of format specifiers in GDScript's string formatting.
Format specifiers are used in placeholders within GDScript strings. These specifiers consist of one or more characters. Some specifiers, like 's', function independently. Others appear before other characters, and some are specific to certain values or character types.
---CHUNK---
Document: gdscript_format_string
Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/gdscript/gdscript_format_string.rst
Summary: This section details the placeholder types used in GDScript format strings and their expected parameter types.

Placeholder types
One and only one of these must always appear as the last character in a format specifier. Apart from s, these require certain types of parameters.

*   s (Simple): Conversion to String by the same method as implicit String conversion.
*   c (Unicode character): A single Unicode character. Accepts a Unicode code point (integer) or a single-character string. Supports values beyond 255.
*   d (Decimal integer): A decimal integer. Expects an integer or a real number (will be floored).
*   o (Octal integer): An octal integer. Expects an integer or a real number (will be floored).
*   x (Hexadecimal integer, lower-case): A hexadecimal integer with lower-case letters. Expects an integer or a real number (will be floored).
*   X (Hexadecimal integer, upper-case): A hexadecimal integer with upper-case letters. Expects an integer or a real number (will be floored).
*   f (Decimal real): A decimal real number. Expects an integer or a real number.
*   v (Vector): A vector. Expects any float or int-based vector object (Vector2, Vector3, Vector4, Vector2i, Vector3i or Vector4i). Will display the vector coordinates in parentheses, formatting each coordinate as if it was a %f, and using the same modifiers.
---CHUNK---
